<p>Wiberg et al., in 1965, reported the reaction between NbCl
 <sub>5</sub> and LiAlH
 <sub>4</sub> in several proportions and temperatures in ether at low temperature [
 <xref rid="B246-materials-12-02724" ref-type="bibr">246</xref>]. Wiberg et al. concluded that the products were a function of the temperature and the excess of LiAlH
 <sub>4</sub> used; the first family of products was [
 <xref rid="B246-materials-12-02724" ref-type="bibr">246</xref>]: 
 <disp-formula>
  <label>(68)</label>
  <math id="mm117">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msub>
      <mi>NbCl</mi>
      <mn>5</mn>
     </msub>
     <mo>+</mo>
     <mn>5</mn>
     <msub>
      <mi>LiAlH</mi>
      <mn>4</mn>
     </msub>
     <mo> </mo>
     <mo>→</mo>
     <mo> </mo>
     <mi>Nb</mi>
     <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
     <msub>
      <mi>AlH</mi>
      <mn>4</mn>
     </msub>
     <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
     <msub>
      <mrow/>
      <mi mathvariant="normal">n</mi>
     </msub>
     <mo>+</mo>
     <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
     <mn>5</mn>
     <mo> </mo>
     <mo>−</mo>
     <mo> </mo>
     <mi>n</mi>
     <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
     <msub>
      <mi>AlH</mi>
      <mn>3</mn>
     </msub>
     <mo>+</mo>
     <mfrac>
      <mrow>
       <mn>5</mn>
       <mo>−</mo>
       <mi>n</mi>
      </mrow>
      <mn>2</mn>
     </mfrac>
     <msub>
      <mi mathvariant="normal">H</mi>
      <mn>2</mn>
     </msub>
     <mo>+</mo>
     <mn>5</mn>
     <mi>LiCl</mi>
     <mo>,</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </disp-formula> when 
 <italic>n</italic> = 3.5 at −70 °C the product was Nb
 <sub>2</sub>(AlH
 <sub>4</sub>)
 <sub>7</sub>, for 
 <italic>n</italic> = 3.0 at −40 °C the product was Nb
 <sub>2</sub>(AlH
 <sub>4</sub>)
 <sub>6</sub>, and for 
 <italic>n</italic> = 2.5 at 20 °C the product was Nb
 <sub>2</sub>(AlH
 <sub>4</sub>)
 <sub>5</sub>. 
</p>
